Example 2: Counter with useEffect
import { useState, useEffect } from "react";

function CounterEffect() {

    const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

    useEffect(() => {
        console.log("Count changed:", count);
    }, [count]);

    return (
        <div>
            <h2>Count: {count}</h2>

            <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>
                Increment
            </button>
        </div>
    );
}

export default CounterEffect;
What happens?

Initial load:

Count changed: 0

Click button:

Count changed: 1
Count changed: 2
Count changed: 3
Example 3: Change Browser Title
import { useState, useEffect } from "react";

function PageTitle() {

    const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

    useEffect(() => {
        document.title = `Count: ${count}`;
    }, [count]);

    return (
        <div>
            <h2>{count}</h2>

            <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>
                Increment
            </button>
        </div>
    );
}

export default PageTitle;

Notice the browser tab title changes.

Dependency Array Rules
Run Once
useEffect(() => {
    console.log("Loaded");
}, []);

Runs only once.

Run When State Changes
useEffect(() => {
    console.log("Count changed");
}, [count]);

Runs whenever count changes.

Run Every Render
useEffect(() => {
    console.log("Rendered");
});

Runs after every render.

